Let $d$ be a divisor of $210$ and let $a= d$, then $b = \dfrac {210^3}{d}$.
In which case we have some $x, y$ in $\mathbb{N}$ where $xy=210^3$ and $x,y$ are coprime.
Now we can let the ordered pair $(u_1, v_1)$ be $(1,210^3)$ and $(210^3,1)$.
With these in mind, we have:
\begin{align*}
  \begin{cases}
    & d = 210 && a = 210 \\
    & v_1 = 1 && \implies d = 210^2 \\
    & u_1 = 1 && \implies a = 210
  \end{cases}
\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}
  \begin{cases}
    & d = 210 && b = 210^2 \\
    & v_1 = 210^2 && \implies a = 210 \\
    & u_1 = 1 && \implies b = 210^3
  \end{cases}.
\end{align*}
But, due to the fact OP stated that $a < b$, then $(u_1, v_1)=(1,210^3)$ is the only valid case. But, of course, $(a,b)$ is also ordered in some way, and so we can optimally have:
\begin{align*}
  \begin{cases}
    & a = d && \implies d = 1, 2,3,5,6,7,10,14,15,21 \\
    & d = \dfrac{210}{d} && \implies d \in \{210,105,70,42,35,30,21,15,14,10\} \\
    & d < 210 && \implies a < b
  \end{cases}
\end{align*}
Thus, the possible values for $a$ are $d= 1,2,3,5,6,7,10,14,15,21$ and there are exactly $10$ possible values for $a$.
